\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\qc\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 Man-Machine Integration: A call to discernment\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 The human race has been making great advances in science and technology
 over the past few centuries, but our understanding of these technologies, or rather
 how to use them properly has not.  Welcome to the age of science, wherein the further
 development of science promises to address all the problems associated with the
 human condition.  Obviously, the Christian should not put his faith in science, 
nor can he believe that science holds the answers to poverty, hunger, pain, violence
 or death, yet this is the worldview which many scientists hold.  The Christian 
must evaluate those things which science produces, and understand them with regard
 to their Creator.  Therefore, when technologies are developed, Christians must 
use discernment in determining their uses, their benefits and consequences, and 
further apply the standards God has given to his children to them.  This essay seeks
 to understand and explore the ethics of the technology associated with man-machine
 integration.\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 Basic Technology:\tab\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240\fi720{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0
\lang1033\fs22\kerning28 The field of human-machine integration is very broad, spanning
 multiple disciplines.  As a result it is necessary, for the sake of time, that 
only a portion of the actual technologies will be addressed.  The four areas of 
technology to be addressed are: Bionics, Neural Interfacing, Radio Frequency Identification
 and Thermal Induction.  It is also necessary to mention that this type of technology
 is still in its infancy.  The basic components required for its development are
 all currently available, but are not yet advanced enough to allow integration with
 the human body for an indefinite period of time.\line\tab The first field to address
 is that of bionics.  As an overview, bionics is a field in which human engineers
 try to replicate nature using mechanical engineering.  For example, in attempting
 to create a bionic human hand, a group of engineers would have to address how the
 hand moves, the functions of skin, tissue, ligaments and bones, and try to replicate
 each of them with mechanical equivalents.\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 The second field to address is that of neural interfacing, otherwise
 known as brain-machine interfacing.  Neural interfacing uses neural imaging and
/or pattern recognition in order to determine the desired action of a person.  There
 are two main types of neural interfacing: invasive and non-invasive.  Non-invasive
 methods use electroencephalography in order to determine the desire of an individual
. (Lebedev 536) This involves attaching electrodes to the scalp which record electrical
 signals which indicate different types of brain activity.  Then, based upon those
 records, a person can be taught how to control something using this type of interface
.  Non-invasive neural interfacing is less accurate than invasive interfacing, but
 also less dangerous, and is also easily removable.  Essentially, non-invasive neural
 interfaces are better if a person does not require an interface for a prolonged
 period of time. \line  Invasive neural interfacing involves the implantation of
 electrodes in order to record and evaluate the firing patterns of pools of neurons
 from inside the brain itself.  When these electrodes are connected to some other
 device, then an individual may be trained to control a device via the use of his
 mind.   The results of this type of training, for the moment, are limited to abstractions
 of the current human experience, and it has not been determined whether or not 
this technology will allow humans to interact with the world in new ways, at least
 on a sensational level. (sight, touch, etc.)  This process also requires brain 
surgery which is both dangerous and costly. \par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 The third field is radio frequency identification, or RFID.  RFID
 uses radio signals tuned to specific frequencies in order to communicate.  There
 are two parts of an RFID system:  a sender and a receiver.  There are two types
 of RFID systems: active and passive.  In passive RFID, the sender emits a radio
 frequency, and the receiver is powered by that frequency.  The receiver then uses
 that power to return information to the emitter.  In active RFID, the sender emits
 information at a radio frequency, and the receiver accepts the information emitted
. (Harmon)  With passive RFID the receiver moves with the user and the sender is
 stationary.  In active RFID, the sender moves with the user and the receiver is
 stationary.  \par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 The fourth field which applies to man-machine integration is thermal
 induction.  For devices which require power to communicate from inside the body
, a continual source of power is needed.  In the case of the human body, it seems
 that thermal induction is the most practical choice.  Recent advances in this technology
 have implied that thermal induction within the human body may be possible on a 
high enough scale to power small devices. Ghovanloo & Najafi say this may be possible
 by leeching excess heat off of muscles in the body.\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28\tab The result of combining these four emerging technologies is 
the creation of devices which can aid the human race (or more likely the rich) overcome
 issues associated with inactive or missing limbs, unsteady hands, permanent injury
, etc.  Yet, this technology is not limited to merely restoring function, but also
 enhancing function.  And it is here, where ethical issues and dilemnas are discovered
.\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 In order to give a better idea of the combined force of these technologies
, here are some examples:  Remote Mind-controlled cars, replacement of a lost limb
 using a bionic prosthetic controlled by the mind, Personal tracking devices, body
 monitors and manipulators, and controlling unmanned military vehicles from afar
. \par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 Biblical examination of technology:\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 The Bible calls Christians to discern what is good, and stay away
 from what is evil.  Discernment is a major biblical theme which is connected with
 wisdom, knowledge and understanding.(Psalm 119:25, Prov. 10:13,17, 17:24, Hosea
 14:9)  Paul{\lang4105\u8217\'92}s prayer in Philippians 1:9-11 shows the true heart
 of why the Christian should seek discernment:  {\super 9}And this is my prayer: 
that your love may abound more and more in knowledge and depth of insight, {\super
10}so that you may be able to discern what is best and may be pure and blameless
 until the day of Christ, {\super 11}filled with the fruit of righteousness that
 comes through Jesus Christ{\lang4105\emdash}to the glory and praise of God.\line
It is for the growth of love, in order to remain blameless before God, and in order
 to bring glory and praise to God. \par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 Ethicality:\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 The main issues with the technologies presented arise from the fields
 of bionics and neural interfacing.  These two areas will generally be what are 
meant when using the term {\lang4105\u8220\'93}technology{\lang4105\u8221\'94} or
 {\lang4105\u8220\'93}implant{\lang4105\u8221\'94}\line  in this section.  In order
 to look at the ethicality of this technology two ideas must be examined: 1) The
 nature of the human person and 2) The reasons for the use of the technology.  Both
 ideas address different types of ethical questions.\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240\fi-360\li720{\pntext 1)\tab}{\*
\pn\pnlvlbody\pndec\pnql\pnstart1\pnindent360{\pntxta )}}{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich
\f0\lang1033\fs22\kerning28 The Human Reality:\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28\tab First, the age-old question of {\lang4105\u8220\'93}what is 
man?{\lang4105\u8221\'94} must be answered.  From a Christian perspective, man is
 the special creation of God, the highlight of all He created on earth, and created
 in His very image.  In order to answer this question well, we must look at the 
entirety of human life.  This entirety is made primarily from the combination of
 mind, soul, body, and the interactions of humanity with itself.  To address these
 topics, the beginning of the story of humanity must be examined.\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 In Genesis 1, God creates the heavens and the earth and everything
 in them.    On the sixth day, after God had created all the animals, He called 
His creation good, but after He created man in His image He called it very good.  
There is something about the human being which improves the reality of every created
 thing.  \par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 God created everything with great intention great detail.  It would
 make very little sense for God to create {\i ex nihilo} without intention, for 
the very nature of the creative enterprise implies intention.  This leads to the
 conviction that God created everything in its form for a specific purpose.\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 Many have looked at Genesis 1:26 and read only that God created 
man in His image, and have proceeded to debate about what that image actually entails
.  In John 4:24 it says {\lang4105\u8220\'93}God is spirit, and his worshipers must
 worship in spirit and in truth.{\lang4105\u8221\'94}  Therefore, if God is spirit
 then it would be reasonable to expect His image to be reflected in a spiritual 
nature, not a physical one.  Therefore, for the sake of simplicity, let us assume
 that being made in God{\lang4105\u8217\'92}s image means that we have intellect
, an immortal soul and the capacity to become more like God.  This poses no problem
, but it must be remembered that the human being is not in sum a spiritual being
.  That is certainly part of man{\lang4105\u8217\'92}s nature, but not the totality
.  There is also the physical nature of the human being, which must also be addressed
.  As has already been stated, God created everything in its form for a specific
 purpose, and it is reasonable to suggest that this also includes the physical human
 body which would be the vessel for the ones who were to bear His image.  It is 
not only a vessel or prison for the soul, but is also an integral part of the way
 the human being was designed from the very beginning.  In fact, the bible teaches
 the Christian to have respect for the body.  One instance of this is 1 Corinthians
 6:19-20 where Paul is speaking telling the Church in Corinth that the human body
 is the temple of the Holy Spirit, and that it is to be used to honour God.  To 
importance of the body to being human is emphasized by the fact that followers of
 Christ will be given new bodies in the resurrection.  One of the evidences of this
 is in John 20 when Jesus appeared to the disciples after his resurrection and showed
 that he did have a real body, and Thomas was able to touch him.  In Colossians 
1, Jesus is called {\lang4105\u8220\'93}the firstborn from among the dead,{\lang4105
\u8221\'94} and that Christians shall be made like Him.  Though the physical body
 will die, a new body will be given at the resurrection, therefore man will never
 exist without a body.  Then it is no overstatement to say that the body plays a
 significant role in what it means to be human.  Yet in saying this, the direct 
consequence for the human person is that there are certain God-ordained limitations
 in traditional human experience.  This simply points to another part of human design
 to be dependent on other humans.  \par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 The design of humans is to be relational.  From the very beginning
, God set in the heart of man the desire for relationship.  In Genesis 2:18, while
 Adam was still alone in his humanity, God said {\lang4105\u8220\'93}It is not good
 for the man to be alone. I will make a helper suitable for him.{\lang4105\u8221
\'94}  Thus, while relationship with God was inherent from the beginning, God also
 established relationship within humanity as well.  In fact, the theme throughout
 the Bible is about God{\lang4105\u8217\'92}s desired relationship with man, and
 man needing a relationship with Him.\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 Thus the Christian{\lang4105\u8217\'92}s view of his own humanity
 must include his mind, body, spirit and relationships in order to properly determine
 the effects of a serious change in part of what makes him human.  Now that the 
nature of the human being has been addressed from a Christian perspective, some 
ethical questions can begin to be answered.\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 In understanding these fundamental truths of the human person, some
 of the proper and improper uses of this technology become apparent.  The proper
 use of this technology would involve restoring function to those individuals with
 missing or damaged body parts.  Ocular implants for those who are blind, a bionic
 leg for someone who lost one, a mind-controlled wheelchair for those who are tetrapalegics
.  The improper use would be that which encourages frivolity.   An example of frivolity
 might be replacing a working human hand with a neutrally-interfaced bionic hand
 with an automated Swiss army knife included.  Unless there is specific purpose 
or good reason as to why a part of the body should be replaced or why an individual
 should be given increased ability to control machines, the ability ought not be
 given to the individual.  The reason for this is mainly founded in the idea that
 there are God-ordained limitations on the human being, and the Christian should
 strive to be content with what God has given him. \par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28  If this view is accepted among Christians there is potential for
 great controversy.  The question at the center of this controversy would be what
 constitutes a {\lang4105\u8220\'93}damaged{\lang4105\u8221\'94} body part.  Where
 is the line drawn between functional and non-functional?  What if the body part
 is functional but cannot be restored to its original body function?  It might seem
 that these are circumstantial, but certain guidelines should be put in place.  
The difference between functional and non-functional is fairly straightforward:  
if the individual is unable to use the body part in question for its designed purpose
, then it is non-functional.  Conversely, if the individual is able to use the body
 part in question for its designed purpose, then the body part is functional.  Certainly
 more qualifications upon those statements could be made, but they are not intended
 to be used as legal guidelines.  The spirit of the statements is enough for the
 purpose of application.  When looking at functional and non-functional body parts
, the issue of impractical functionality.  This is where the body part has a degree
 of functionality, but it is impractical for the completion of everyday tasks.  
An example of this might be a man who has multiple sclerosis, located centrally 
in his fingers, trying to type on a traditional keyboard.  He is able to move his
 knuckles, but unable to feel or move his fingers.  In this case, he should be able
 to replace his fingers (or his hand in case the disease progresses) if he desires
, because while they have a degree of function, they disallow him from doing work
.\par}

