\fs22\kerning28    \par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240\fi-360\li720{\pntext 2)\tab}{\*
\pn\pnlvlbody\pndec\pnql\pnstart2\pnindent360{\pntxta )}}{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich
\f0\lang1033\fs22\kerning28 The Human Motivation:\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 The second issue which must be explored is the individual{\lang4105
\u8217\'92}s motivation for desiring the body enhancements. This section deals primarily
 with the enhancement of the human body, not the restoration, as restoration is 
a good and acceptable motivation.  The question remains, why does motivation matter
 with regard to the enhancement of the body?  The answer is that the motivation 
influences the use of the enhancement, and without the motivation the technology
 would not be sought after.  The human person desires many things, and while desires
 are good, the true nature of the desire is difficult to ascertain.  Jeremiah 17
:9 says, {\lang4105\u8220\'93}The heart is deceitful above all things and beyond
 cure.  Who can understand it?{\lang4105\u8221\'94}  In other words, what a person
 desires is not always good for him.  The point of examining a person{\lang4105\u8217
\'92}s desires is to ensure that the technology will not become a detriment to the
 person{\lang4105\u8217\'92}s spiritual or intellectual life.  If a misplaced desire
 is fulfilled, then the result is a misuse of the object of desire.  A person may
 desire an implant for the sake of laziness or comfort, but the reality is that 
one implant will never be enough to sate such a desire.  The result is that the 
person is very likely to continue to exchange his body for convenience, and by so
 doing show contempt for the body which God has given him.  This, of course, is 
a simplified line of reasoning, but the essence of the argument is valid.  The underlying
 truth of the argument is this: If the motivation for implantation is discontentment
 with the body, (with exception to damaged or non-functioning human bodies) then
 the person should not be enhanced.  There must first be contentment with how the
 human being is made, so that the person may also be content when he is enhanced
.       \line If there are good and bad motivations for being enhanced, then how
 do you differentiate between them?  There may be some motivations which fall outside
 the designation of good or bad, being a combination of both, in which case a person
 should defer to the wisdom of those individuals in the church who know God and 
practice godliness in their lives.\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28  That being said, what do invalid motivations look like?  These 
motivations are primarily centered on the individual, and would be primarily aimed
 at circumventing personal weaknesses.  For the Christian, weakness is not something
 to be ignored or despised, but addressed and persevered.  When Paul asked God to
 remove the thorn in his flesh, God replied {\lang4105\u8220\'93}My grace is sufficient
 for you, for my power is made perfect in weakness.{\lang4105\u8221\'94}(2 Corinthians
 12:9)  For this reason, Christians must accept their personal weaknesses, and not
 only try to remove them, but rely on God and persevere through them.  Even though
 weakness is undesirable, it points the Christian to God, and causes him to rely
 more fully upon Him.  For example, a short-sighted person may be reminded of his
 dependence upon God because when he awakes, he is unable to see the world clearly
 without his glasses.\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 The problem with being motivated by weakness is that the purpose
 is to improve the individual, instead of enabling him.\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28  For example, a man who is beaten by others might want to use implants
 so that he could defend himself.  The desire to defend oneself is good, but using
 implants to achieve that goal is not acceptable.  The root of this problem is not
 in physical weakness, but in societal cruelty.  Thus, while the implants would 
help the man being beaten for a time, those who beat him would find another to beat
 and the problem itself would not be remedied. \par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 In contrast, what do valid motivations look like?  Valid motivations
 are centered upon benefiting others, and enabling a person to perform a task more
 effectively. (Charter for Health Care Workers)  This is because the purpose of 
the enhancement is not in order to mask personal weakness, but to help the individual
 be more effective in what they are already doing.  An example of this might be 
found in policing.  It would be beneficial for a police officer to have enhancements
 so that he could catch criminals more effectively, and reduce the risk of his own
 injury or death.  This is acceptable because the police officer does his job for
 the sake of others, and the enhancements would help hi m do so more effectively
.  While this does not address the deeper issue of crime, it does allow the deeper
 issue to be addressed.  The function of police officers is to enforce the law, 
not to change it.  Therefore, for the deeper issues of crime to be addressed, the
 lawmakers will have to address the law.  The difference between the beaten man 
and the policeman is that one is personal, and one is occupational.\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 Implants should not be used to address the symptoms of deeper societal
 problems, but rather to address the deeper problems themselves, if possible.  In
 the case of the beaten man, technology can only shift the problem onto others, 
not solve it, and thus it is a personal problem.  In the case of the police officer
, the technology aids him in his occupation, so it addresses an occupational need
.  Implants are not an easy solution or remedy to human problems or weaknesses.  
They ought not to be viewed as improvements upon the human body, but rather as very
 effective tools.  \par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 Thus in looking at the human person as a whole, and the motivations
 for using implants, an ethical guideline is set in place.  By no means is it a 
complete ethic, but deals with the conceptual issues of the technology, in relation
 to a Christian worldview, which must be addressed before it is used.\par}

