\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 Relationships:\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 The issue of human relationships was alluded to earlier, and it 
will be discussed briefly here.  Most human relationships require an element of 
personal experience, and this experience allows or disallows people to interact 
well with each other.  The use of implantable technology would influence human experience
 in its scope and in its ability to be related between individuals.  This has far
 reaching consequences, which inhibit a person from relating to others in the present
 or in the past.  This is not a problem introduced exclusively by the technology
, but is rather emphasized by it.  For example, if an enhanced person understood
 himself to be superior in some way to an unenhanced person, he might begin to have
 contempt for that person.  In this way, human relationship has deteriorated due
 to an individual{\lang4105\u8217\'92}s personal pride in his enhancement.  A parallel
 example more apparent in modernity would be how some people view people from ancient
 times as intellectually inferior or ignorant, and view people from the present 
time as intellectually enlightened.   Certainly the present age has more information
 and observations about the world, but this has no bearing on the intellectual capabilities
 of those who came before.  As a result of this {\lang4105\u8220\'93}intellectual
 comparison{\lang4105\u8221\'94} between the modern and ancient world, some individuals
 do not have the ability to relate to the thinkers of the ancient world.  In the
 same way, the Christian must understand that tools (or enhancements) are not to
 his own credit, but allow him to use his abilities more fully.\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 Apologetics:\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 The issues described so far deal with an ethic which can only be
 supported from a Christian worldview, however, not all are Christian.  In realizing
 this, Christians will be required to give an apology or defense of why they restrict
 their use of this technology.  While the primary reasons for a Christian to do 
so remain in his worldview, the apology consists of reasons why a non-Christian 
would also act in the same manner.  An argument for remaining bodily independent
 from corporations could be used as the basis for an apologetic.  \par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 RFID technology is primarily one of passing information wirelessly
 and requires a medium through which this information must be transferred.  This
 medium would most likely be via large corporations or governments.  The medium 
gives those in control of it access to the personal information of the individual
, and allows them to use it for their own benefit.  There are many arguments against
 the centralization of information in governments or corporations, as among other
 things, it is viewed as an infringement of privacy and civil liberties.(Albrecht
, McIntyre)  Further, the access to information via the RFID chip is not fully encrypted
, anyone with the right kind of emitter/receiver could access the data from the 
chip.(p199 Albrecht, McIntyre)  It would require a lot of faith in the government
 and/or corporations in order to accept that they would use the information responsibly
 and respect the privacy of those using it.\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 A note concerning contentment:\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 Contentment is not a new concept for the Christian, it is something
 to be desired and pursued.  As always, contentment is not found in possessions 
or ideas, but rather the acceptance of one{\lang4105\u8217\'92}s gifts and abilities
, the rewards of one{\lang4105\u8217\'92}s labour, and the desire to be all that
 one is able to be.   In view of this, Christians need to understand body enhancements
 as something which aids them in doing what they were already capable of doing, 
and not as a means to become something that they are not or to accommodate some 
trait or skill which they lack.  1 Timothy 6:6-9 says, {\lang4105\u8220\'93}\~{\super
6}But godliness with contentment is great gain. {\super 7}For we brought nothing
 into the world, and we can take nothing out of it. {\super 8}But if we have food
 and clothing, we will be content with that. {\super 9}People who want to get rich
 fall into temptation and a trap and into many foolish and harmful desires that 
plunge men into ruin and destruction.{\lang4105\u8221\'94}  The principle in this
 passage is money, however it displays a truth which can be applied to body enhancements
.  They cannot cause you to be content.  The acquisition of more leads to the desire
 for more.  Contentment is an active choice, a conscious thought and a safeguard
 for a person against himself.  Body enhancements will prove useful and desirable
, and therefore be seductive.  Christians must be aware of their call to be content
 with what they have, and particularly not to acquire body enhancements without 
an appropriate cause.\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 Bringing it all together:\par}

\pard\nowidctlpar\nooverflow\sl275\slmult1\sa240{\dbch\af1\loch\af0\hich\f0\lang1033
\fs22\kerning28 The BMI, bionics and RFID technologies offer a promising future.  
When combined, these technologies allow for the creation of tools which restore 
or enhance human body function.  This offers great hope for the restoration of those
 with lost limbs or faulty body parts.  The Christian is called to both embrace 
this technology and scrutinize it.  If he is to use this technology, then it must
 be for the sake of fulfilling his responsibilities more excellently, with proper
 motives, and with due consideration of how it will affect the ways he interacts
 with others.  The desire for its use must not come out of selfishness, ambition
 or ego, but rather from the desire to do all things to their best ability.  They
 are to do this for the sake of others and in order to honour God.  Therefore, Christians
 are called to discern the nature of their own desires, and to test desires of others
.  Not everyone who wants enhancements should be permitted to receive them, as there
 are few Christians who could qualify.  The implementation of this technology in
 the Christian community is secondary to the pursuit of godly lives, and it is imperative
 it remain as such.  The hope is that the Christian community might be able to lead
 the ethics movement for body enhancements and neural implants, but it cannot do
 so if the technology negatively impacts the spiritual and social life of the user
.  If care, support and discernment are used by those who employ this technology
, then Christians may be able to implement these technologies on a wider scale.  
This technology could be extremely useful and influential, but Christians would 
first have to use it to heal, and only afterwards to examine proper, godly enhancement
.{\f0\lang4105\par}}

